            <p>Ἰησοῦς Ἀλώθ
                </p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" ana="#b1" xml:id="jeru0070.translation" corresp="#jeru0070.transcription">
            <p>Jesus aloe</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Ossuary has inner ledge on two sides, low feet, and flat, cut-to-measure lid. Inscription is on the lid. Sukenik offers three interpretations of the second word: it might come from the Hebrew root אלה "to wail, lament," though the use of the root in this sense is very rare; it might be an adjectival form of a place name; or it might be a nickname or name transliterated from the Hebrew אהלות, "aloe." The latter interpretation is favored by Kane and the author, who mention other nicknames deriving from aromatic plant names (like balsam, cinnamon, saffron, and perhaps thyme) and note that the addition of a nickname here differentiates the deceased from another Ἰησοῦς buried in the same tomb. Ἀλώθ is also attested in Egypt as a male name.</p>
         </div>
